##1,000 new cases confirmed in one day: Iran trapped by epidemic

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

Iran, at the crossroads of Eurasia, faces an increasing risk of spreading outwards.

An escape

At 7 pm on March 5, Cui Siqi, a Chinese teacher living in Tehran, the capital of Iran, dragged her luggage into an isolation cell in Lanzhou New District, Gansu Province. The flight from Tehran to Lanzhou takes five hours each way, but it is nearly 24 hours since he was waiting to take off from Tehran airport. He finally "fled" Tehran.

The mask on his face was put on by the paramedic before he boarded the plane. It hurt his face, and now he can finally tear it off. He was careful not to take it out of the bag before boarding the plane. On the plane, he felt the mask was in the wrong place, like a buckle into the bone, he would open and close the tears will come out, but he did not dare to move. After a colleague gave him a tissue, he wiped it slightly, fearing that he would rub the virus into his eyes. He still wore goggles that served as goggles, but they were too tight to breathe, and he closed his eyes as hard as he could after taking them off.

On the way to the supermarket two days before he returned home, Cui Siqi put on a new and old mask, sunglasses and a plastic bag over his head. When he arrived at the supermarket, two Iranian staff members wondered: Why is it so? They weren't even wearing masks.

The decision to return to China came on February 29th. On Feb. 19, the Iranian government confirmed the first case of a new coronavirus in the country. A week later, dozens or dozens of new cases were reported daily, but more than 100 were suddenly reported after Feb. 27, and the number rose to 143 on geometric progression.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the morning of the 29th, someone from the embassy contacted Cui Siqi and asked him if he had any difficulties in his life and if he was willing to return home. All he said was that the water heater was broken and he was afraid to have it fixed. Tristram's house in Tehran is remote, with few people around, and he believes it is relatively safe. He bought enough food at the market to live for a month.

Unexpectedly, on the 29th, Iran confirmed 205 new cases. In the domestic family and friends saw the news, worried, let Cui Siqi hurry back to the country. That night, Cui Siqi contacted the embassy staff that the charter flight may be over after not. Trace Qi thought, can not delay, he filled out the registration form for return to the country.

On March 3, the embassy set up a wechat group, aggregating everyone's passport information to airlines. The next day, Cui and 145 other Chinese citizens boarded a commercial charter flight to Lanzhou.

Before boarding the plane from the ferry, four paramedics surrounded him: changing his mask, spraying disinfectant, washing his hands, taking his temperature, and checking his ticket again. Along the way, Cui filled out three health declaration forms, took her temperature four times, drew blood once, took a throat test, and had a thrilling experience: After the plane landed in Lanzhou, cui Siqi heard the customs officer ask the front row passengers: Fever for a few days? There was a feverish passenger sitting diagonally behind Tristraki. Fortunately, Cui Siqi recalled, did not hear their cough along the way, these people with suspected symptoms concentrated off the plane first. Drizzie.these people should be at the hospital by now.

The journey is long, "sometimes it's waiting for everyone to check in, sometimes it's waiting for everyone to check in, sometimes it's not knowing what to wait for, " Cui told scidev.net. In spite of the delay, at least he got back to China without a hitch.

Chinese travel blogger long Wei, who is still waiting to return home from Tehran, was not so lucky. He arrived in Iran on January 17 and has been in the country for more than a month. Long told the Financial Times that he had bought a ticket home for Aeroflot on March 8, after which the price of the ticket increased tenfold, from more than 2,000 to more than 20,000. But on March 6, long canceled his ticket after Tehran airport refused to give him a boarding pass for Chinese who bought the same flight. He joined a crowd of 500 at the Chinese Embassy in Tehran to gauge their willingness to return home, but the flight was long overdue.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the long micro camera, the market is still all open, people as usual shopping, handling and conversation, only occasionally one or two passers-by wearing masks. Before Cui Siqi left, he saw that the shops where he usually bought Naan were still bustling with activity. Naan is the staple food of the local people. Naan made in the shops is kept on an iron shelf. After paying the bill, the customers hand-carry Naan and leave. Sometimes cash comes and sometimes Naan comes. Cui Siqi felt afraid, he's switching to pasta that needs to be cooked every time.

On the second day of isolation in Lanzhou, at noon local time on March 7, the Iranian Ministry of Health reported that in the past 24 hours, Iran added 1,076 newly confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia, a cumulative total of 5,823 confirmed cases. Earlier, on March 2, a member of Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei's Advisory Council died of pneumonia. Iran's first female vice president, Sumy, was also infected with the new coronavirus, which infected the head of the country's emergency health service on Wednesday. Iranian President Rohani says the new coronavirus has spread to almost all provinces.

A holy city and two gatherings

News of a new coronavirus infection in Iran appeared on Feb. 19, when Triesky was checking Instagram. The first two confirmed cases were in the holy city of Qom, which led to the outbreak.

Qom, a Shiite Mecca of Islam in northwestern Iran and a Land Transit Center with a permanent population of 1.2 million, is visited by millions of people each year. According to the Shia version of the hadith, "if there are eight doors to heaven, three are in Qom. " .

Tristram, who has traveled to Qom, saw that in the mosque, where worshippers sleep, read the scriptures and Hadith, and worship in the direction of the Holy City, which is a part of daily life for local worshippers. By Sunday, when the crowds are denser, pilgrims have the habit of kissing and touching the altar, which could become a huge source of infection.

After the announcement of the first confirmed case of the new coronavirus, the Iranian government ordered the closure of the shrine and mosque in Qom, the worst affected area, but the city's clergy boycotted it for several days. On February 22, in the official news in Iran, Sheikh Saidi, the Custodian of the Holy Sepulchre in Qom, opposed the closure of the Holy Sepulchre, saying that "the Holy Sepulchre can not be closed but should be encouraged as much as possible" , because "the Holy Land is a place of healing, not disease. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Yuxuan, a longtime observer of international affairs on Iran, told this newspaper that Iran's theocratic system gives religious figures great power, and even if the government wanted to close religious sites, it would not be easy, the failure to close religious sites further spread the disease.

Qom residents are still refusing to comply with a provincial Security Council order to close the shrine after the Iranian authorities cancelled a three-day religious festival scheduled for early March. On February 28th Iran cancelled a 41-year-old Friday service across the country.

But Qom has yet to close down the city, leaving residents free to travel. Even if the mosque is closed, devout people will still choose to go to another city's mosque for worship, which will lead to the spread of Qom disease. Although Friday prayers have been canceled, many worshippers attend other times of the week, and are expected to attend a mass service at a mosque.

Iranian President Rohani told a cabinet meeting on February 26th that his country has no plans to put any towns under sanitary quarantine. On Feb. 27, the leader, Ali Khamenei, said in a video of his speech on coronavirus that he supported the Ministry of Health's policy of "not quarantining cities in affected areas. ". According to the file, Qom makes 300,000 trips a day to and from Tehran, while shopping malls, hospitals, and subway prayer rooms are open, and subway and bazaar crowds continue to gather.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
She also recalled with concern two mass rallies: a march on Feb. 11 to mark the forty-one th anniversary of the Islamic Revolution in Iran, and parliamentary elections on Feb. 21.

Iran's National Day Parade begins in Plaza de la Revolucin, near the Revolutionary University of Tehran, and travels West, three or four subway stations to Freedom Tower Square. The whole road was crowded with people, people next to each other, making it impossible for traffic to pass. Tristraki thinks the virus was already lurking in the crowd.

Even if a diagnosis is made on February 19th, the government is reluctant to call off parliamentary elections on February 21st. Tristram watched on television as people went to the polls, almost without masks.

"The epidemic actually occurred in Iran in January, but the situation in Iran has been volatile recently, and the government did not release the epidemic until February 19, " said Hua Liming, a special researcher at the China Institute of International Studies and a former Chinese ambassador to Iran, "In such a situation, the Iranian government is facing continuous anti-government demonstrations and the government has not cancelled the demonstrations and elections to ensure political security. "

In Kuen Bin's view, the government did not quickly take quarantine and other hard measures to deal with the epidemic, but also to ensure economic and social stability. A shutdown would further devastate Iran's fragile economy, already under pressure from U.S. sanctions, and could lead to panic and looting, leading to shortages and unrest. Economic Protection and absolute control of the epidemic, can only take care of one head.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the first week of the Tehran outbreak, coffee shops were still crowded and public places were crowded, Yin told the Financial Times. On the one hand, the government played down the situation, and on the other hand, Iran recently faced a lot of difficulties with sanctions and rising prices, and coronaviruses are only one of the difficulties.

On February 28th World Health Organization raised the global risk of a new pneumonia outbreak to "very high" .

The risk of proliferation

On Feb. 19, after hearing that Qom had confirmed that two of them were infected with the new crown, she went to the supermarket to buy groceries and talk to the Afghans who were selling flowers at the door, telling them to be careful, too. His Farsi was so inarticulate, they thought he said they were dead. Tristram explained that it was just a diagnosis. A few hours later, two people were dead.

At 4 p.m. , she went to the drugstore and bought 30 masks for a total of 300,000 rials, about 15 yuan. The next day he wanted to buy some more disinfectant, and as soon as he walked into the drugstore at nine in the morning, the man waved his hand and said, we're out of masks. He went to another store, and there was a limit of four masks. A student later told Tristraqi that some masks in Tehran had risen to as much as 15 yuan -- nearly a week's worth of food for the average family in Tehran. That may be why many people on the road still don't wear masks, Cui thought.

Sonia, a 27 year old Iranian, has been out of work for so long that she can not afford the expensive masks. She has a master's degree in industrial engineering, but can only work part-time as a tour guide in Iran. On Jan. 10, the White House said in a statement that President Donald Trump signed an executive order authorizing the Treasury Department to impose sanctions on several sectors of the Iranian economy, including construction, mining, manufacturing and textiles. Relations between the United States and Iran have become more strained, with many tourists no longer visiting the country, and Sonia unable to get a job and essentially no income.

On February 28, Sonia developed a fever and coughed. She went to the hospital, and the doctor said it was just the flu, no treatment. Sonia remained anxious, unable to vouch for the reliability of the doctor's diagnosis because there was no reagent. But she had to go home and isolate herself.

Zhang Yuxuan told this newspaper that Iran can cope with basic drugs and treatment, but in infectious disease prevention and response capacity is weak. Iran's health care importers say they can not buy the test because of U. S. economic sanctions.

China provides assistance to the Iranian government and people

On 21 February, the International Financial Action Task Force on money laundering blacklisted Iran. Imb told the Financial Times that the international anti-money Laundering Agency has repeatedly given Iran grace to pass international anti-money laundering agreements with its government. Iran was blacklisted by the international anti money laundering body, the Intolerance, after the country's parliament passed the agreement but the expert meeting failed to pass it. Blacklisting would subject all transactions with Iran to greater scrutiny. "Many international companies are willing to provide Iran with the new Crown Test Kit, but we are unable to send them money, " said Farad, director of the Iranian Medical Equipment Importers Association, nearly 16,000 suspected cases remain undiagnosed in Iran.

Sonia, who was quarantined at home, told Longwei that many young people could not be treated in hospitals. Worried that she would not be able to get the test, she sent a message to Longwei on March 5: "The Iranian epidemic will peak this week. It will be a disaster. YOU HAVE TO LEAVE EARLY! "

Iran is at a "crossroads" in Eurasia and may yet spread as Shia pilgrims from other countries make the pilgrimage to Qom. Confirmed cases in Iraq, Lebanon, Afghanistan, Bahrain and Kuwait have all travelled to Iran. Hua Liming said that if Iran does not completely close the border and take measures constantly, there may be a large-scale spread in the Middle East.
